<h3>Element sizing</h3>

<p>For the sizing options, like <a href="{{root_path}}layout-modes/masonry.html#columnwidth"><code>masonry: columnWidth</code></a> and <a href="{{root_path}}layout-modes/masonry.html#gutter"><code>masonry: gutter</code></a>, you may set these options to an <i>Element</i> or <i>String</i>, in addition to a <i>Number</i>.</p>

``` html
<div id="container">
  <div class="grid-sizer"></div>
  <div class="item"></div>
  <div class="item"></div>
  ...
</div>
```

<p>With a <i>String</i>, Isotope will use the string as a selector to get the first matching element within the container element. The size of that element is then used.</p>

``` js
var $container = $('#container').isotope({
  itemSelector: '.item',
  masonry: {
    columnWidth: '.grid-sizer'
  }
});
```

<div class="warning">
  <p>If you are using element sizing, be sure to set <a href="#itemselector"><code>itemSelector</code></a> as well, so the sizing element does not get used in the layout.</p>
</div>

<p>With an <i>Element</i>, Isotope will use its outer width to set the value of the related property.</p>

``` js
  masonry: {
    columnWidth: $container.find('.grid-sizer')[0]
  }
```

<p>This allows you to control the size of the Isotope layout just with your CSS. This is useful for responsive layouts, keeping control within CSS so you can rely on media queries.</p>

``` css
/* 5 columns by default */
.grid-sizer { width: 20%; }

@media screen and (min-width: 720px) {
  /* 10 columns for larger screens */
  .grid-sizer { width: 10%; }
}
```

